	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=5906&mid=99044917675926>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=5906&mid=99044917675926>That's not quite the way it works...</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=5906&mid=99044917675926#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, May 21st 8:46 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p><br>You're right on as far as the mainhand vs. offhand stuff.&nbsp;&nbsp;Fast weapons with good ratios are superior in your mainhand. For mainhand, if the ratio is the same, take the one with the lowest delay so you get the damage bonus as frequently as possible.<br><br>However, saying you're better off with a 12/26 in offhand instead of a Lamentation is incorrect.  All that matters in offhand is the ratio.  Take the delay and divide by the damage....the lower the number, the better the weapon will be in your offhand (ignoring procs and damage shields).<br><br>Anything with a 2.0 (Jade Mace (18/9), CSS (24/12)) will produce pretty much equivalent damage results in the OFFhand (In the MAINhand, the Mace is SIGNIFICANTLY better than the CSS).  A lam, at 19/9=2.1 is slightly worse than either the CSS or mace in your offhand and your examples of 26/12=2.17 and 25/11=2.27 are a bit worse that that.<br><br></p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
